```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

We are to determine the IUPAC name of the single major alkene formed when $(R)-3-bromo-4-methylhexane$ is treated with excess KOtBu in tert-butanol at 40 Â°C.

First, we need to identify the reaction. The reaction involves the conversion of an alkene to a more substituted alkene via elimination. In this case, the starting material is $(R)-3-bromo-4-methylhexane$.  The reaction will proceed via E2 elimination.  The reaction with KOtBu in tert-butanol will favor the formation of a more substituted alkene due to the enhanced basicity of the KOtBu reagent.

Step 1:  KOtBu acts as a strong base, removing a proton from the carbon adjacent to the bromine atom. This generates an enolate.

Step 2: The enolate then attacks the carbon bearing the bromine, resulting in elimination of HBr and formation of the alkene. Since the starting material has a bromine atom, the alkene will be a product of E2 elimination.

Step 3: The reaction proceeds through the formation of a carbocation intermediate.

Step 4:  The carbocation is stabilized by the adjacent methyl group, facilitating the formation of the alkene.

Therefore, the major product is $(R)-3-bromo-4-methyl-1-butene$.

\end{document}
```

$$\boxed{{(R)-3-bromo-4-methyl-1-butene}}$$
